Part A

A/B testing to test the null hypothesis "there is no significant difference between the two traders" and the alternative hypothesis of there being a significant difference between the two traders, with alpha set to 0.05. A market session will run with the specification mentioned on the brief. Start time and end time are set to 0 and 3600 seconds (1 hour) respectively with order interval of 60 seconds in parts A-C. This was chosen so sufficient data collection and trades take place in each sessions. After the simulation are complete the accumulated average profit of each trader type is taken. To do hypothesis testing, the collected averages, are passed into Shapiro-Wilk test to understand their distribution, then either t-test or Mann-Whitney-U test are utilised as the parametric and non-parametric test respectively. Different helper functions are used and are in helper.py with explanation of what they do.

Since the market is populated with similar ratios of buyers and sellers of each type, the variance of the two trader's profits is also roughly similar. As the output show, both datasets are following a normal distribution therefore, a t-test can be used.

In[]:
_, p_val50 = stats.ttest_ind(n50mean_zic, n50mean_shvr)
print(p_val50, 'p val for 50 sessions')
_, p_val500 = stats.ttest_ind(n500mean_zic, n500mean_shvr)
print(p_val500, 'p val for 500 sessions')

0.4100452817469036 p val for 50 sessions
0.9907804259631603 p val for 500 sessions

In the simulated market sessions, the p value for both sessions, is above the threshold of 0.05, meaning we do not have sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis. In other words, we can conclude that there is no significant difference between the two trader's performance when comparing the average profit per session.

PART B

Below, modifies the previously used code to accommodate changes to ratios by collecting and returning their average profit at the end of each session in a pair. For each pair of data, they will be tested to see whether they are normally distributed using Shapiro-Wilk and then appropriate hypothesis testing is applied. Another thing to consider is the variance of the data, since there are different number of traders in the market, the variance difference will be high, so Welch's t-test is utilised here when data is parametric.

However, as the number of sessions is increased, for the ratios where there are less shavers in the market, the difference becomes significant. As the ratios get to the extreme ends where all traders are shavers, the few zic traders in the market start giving higher average profit. Finally for the case of equal ratios, there is no difference between the two traders as observed before. In conclusion, Shavers perform best in a market dominated by zic traders and as the number of shavers increase, zic traders perform better.

PART C

Four trader types with different populations being tested to see which is the best. Having 'GVWY', 'SHVR', 'ZIC' and 'ZIP' traders at a predefined ratios below (note: to gather all permutations, np.roll is used). P values obtained are using either Anova test or Kruskal test depending on whether data is parametric or non-parametric, all means collected being normal is very unlikely, therefore only the non-parametric test (Kruskal) is expected to be used. Here rejecting the null hypothesis means there is a significant difference in the market but does not determine which trader is the best. Having a p value lower than 0.05 is expected in all sessions, and further analysis is needed to determine the best trader. Here a total of 100 independent sessions are ran on each ratio to obtain enough data for analysis and to allow the zip trader to adjust its hyperparameters better.

PART D.1:

To replicate the experiment, a single zipsh trader is in the market with 20 other zic traders, where the zipsh is a buyer. Goal is to evaluate zipsh's performance and monitor its improvement over each day. 30 independent runs are done to collect ZIPSH's average profit per second for each of its mutations to then plot it to understand whether there is an improvement after each mutation. Here k is set to 4, optimizer is 'ZIPSH' for its stochastic hill climber and a single session lasts 30 days and the evaluation stage remains untouched. The order intervals are set to 30 seconds, supply is (50,75) and demand curves are (125, 150) so zipsh can make profit and adapt how much. The initial hyperparameter beta and marginal_buy and are set to very low values (0.01 and 0.05 respectively) to highlight the adaptive process of zipsh.

In[]:
#30 sessions, start=0 end= 60*60*24*30 (30 days)
#hyper = [[b, m, ca, cr, mb]], index == day
n = 30
start_time=0
end_time=60*60*24*30
supply=(50, 75)
buy=(125, 150)
buyer_spec = [('ZIPSH', 1, {'k': 4, 'optimizer': 'ZIPSH'}), ('ZIC', 10)]
seller_spec = [('ZIC', 10)]
zipsh_profit, zic_profit, total_avg_profit_perS, hyper_params = run_market_sim_D("replicate", n, supply, buy, start_time, end_time, "replicate_avg_balance.csv", "replicate_strats.csv", buyer_spec, seller_spec)
betas = hyper_params[0]
momentums = hyper_params[1]
c_a = hyper_params[2]
c_r = hyper_params[3]
initial_margin = hyper_params[4]

The independent runs show that the single zipsh trader is indeed making a profit and improving itself in the market and returning a higher profit from the starting point. From extreme cases where it can make up to 500% the initial profit, with some cases where the profit is more modest. This is not always the case as there are times where the trader ends the session with a profit of 0 or less than. There seems to be a relation between the learning rate beta vals and the profit zipsh returns as the beta steadily increases, the profit seems to do the same. This is specially the case if the momentum values do not increase significantly since dramatic shifts seem to always result less profit than before. This can be due to having unstable momentum updates or overshooting the optimal solution leading to a dramatic decrease in the profit, as shown by the figures below (first few are plotted). The algorithm often switches to extreme values for marginal buy which leads it to have the highest profit however it does not adjust for low margins therefore struggling to make profit on lower trades. In conclusion, if the correct mutation is chosen with a steady increase in the beta vals while momentum is kept to a lower value, the trader starts to improve and return a profit, however when there is a dramatic change, the profitability of the traders falls massively.

In[]:
for i in range(5):
    plot_params_pps(total_avg_profit_perS[i], betas[i], momentums[i], c_a[i], c_r[i], initial_margin[i], i+1)

The data is tested for normality using Shapiro-wilk, and either a one sample t-test or Wilcoxon t-test is applied to determine statistical significance. For a single sample size as we have here, the Wilcoxon signed-rank test is used to assess whether the median of the sample is equal to zero or close to it, ie no profit was made. The data here is the average increase in profit for the single zipsh trader within each 30 independent runs. The hypothesis here is that zipsh's profit returns are not statistically significant with alpha of 0.05.

The output show that the p value is less than the threshold 0.05, therefore we have enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis. The increase in profit returned by zipsh is statistically significant meaning it does improve over time.

D2

The effeciveness of ZIPSH trader is evaluated when an extreme market shock happens. To setup the experiment, all vraiables are set to the same as D1 while at mid point of each session, a shift in the demand and supply range happens. This effectively will have the previous adaptation of the trader change as the the market equilibrium changes massively. Goal here is to evaluate whether the zipsh can adapt and still return a profit in a market with only 10 zic traders, instead of 20 total. The reduction is done in an attemp to reduce the noise in the market. The expectation is the profit to be noisy but have an upwards trend as the hill climber adjusts zip's hyper parameterss however to test whether high momentum swings effect the profitablity of the zipsh, This parameter has been hardcoded in bse to always be between 0 and 0.1 instead of (0,1) (line 1357 in bse.py)

The results show that the market is noisier than ever, making it extremely difficult for the zipsh trader to consistently turning a profit. The shock effects can be seen when there is a sudden spike in the profit of zipsh. The results show that the trader is indeed improving overtime and returning the profit and somewhat does adjust when the market shift happens. However, at some instances it struggles to make any profit, with the hyperparameter values not updating at all. The lower momentum value did not lead to any improvement in the algorithm and has only slowed down the process of adaptation and significantly reduced profitability, leading to the conclusion that it indeed needs to be higher than what was currently set and lower than what the default was for the best results. The beta value followed the same logic that, as it was constantly increasing, the profit also increased. There didnt seem to be a pattern for the learning rate when the market shock occurred, as it randomly changed regardless of the changes happening within the market.

To do a statistical significance test, data will be test for normality, and then either one sample t-test or Wilcoxon test utilised. Due to the market shock, it is expected for the data not being normalised as the profits will increase as the trades get larger.

def printWordCount(filepath):

    with io.open(filepath, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f:

    word_count = 0
    for cell in nb.worksheets[0].cells:
        if cell.cell_type == "markdown":
            word_count += len(cell['source'].replace('#', '').lstrip().split(' '))
    print("Word count: " + str(word_count) + ". Limit is 2000 words.")
